instructions:
## Set up Auth0 authentication in a Next.js project

### 1. Create an Auth0 application
- Go to [manage.auth0.com](https://manage.auth0.com) → Applications → Create Application.
- Choose **Regular Web Application** (not SPA — Next.js renders server-side).
- Note your **Domain**, **Client ID**, and **Client Secret** from the Settings tab.
- Under **Allowed Callback URLs**, add: `http://localhost:3000/api/auth/callback`
- Under **Allowed Logout URLs**, add: `http://localhost:3000`
- Under **Allowed Web Origins**, add: `http://localhost:3000`
- Add production URLs to each field when you deploy (e.g., `https://yourdomain.com/api/auth/callback`).

### 2. Install the Auth0 Next.js SDK
```bash
npm install @auth0/nextjs-auth0
```
- This is the official Auth0 SDK for Next.js. It supports both App Router and Pages Router.
- Do NOT use the generic `auth0-js` library — it is for SPAs and does not handle server-side sessions.

### 3. Set environment variables
- Create or update `.env.local`:
```env
AUTH0_SECRET='use [openssl rand -hex 32] to generate a 32-byte value'
AUTH0_BASE_URL='http://localhost:3000'
AUTH0_ISSUER_BASE_URL='https://YOUR_AUTH0_DOMAIN'
AUTH0_CLIENT_ID='YOUR_CLIENT_ID'
AUTH0_CLIENT_SECRET='YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET'
```
- `AUTH0_SECRET` must be at least 32 characters. Generate with: `openssl rand -hex 32`
- `AUTH0_ISSUER_BASE_URL` must include `https://` and your full Auth0 domain (e.g., `https://dev-abc123.us.auth0.com`).
- NEVER commit `.env.local` to git — it should already be in `.gitignore`.

### 4. Create the Auth0 route handler (App Router)
- Create `app/api/auth/[auth0]/route.ts`:
```ts
import { handleAuth } from '@auth0/nextjs-auth0';

export const GET = handleAuth();
```
- This single handler automatically sets up `/api/auth/login`, `/api/auth/logout`, `/api/auth/callback`, and `/api/auth/me`.
- Do NOT manually create separate route handlers for each endpoint — `handleAuth()` covers all of them.

### 5. Wrap the app with Auth0Provider
- Update `app/layout.tsx` to wrap children with `UserProvider`:
```tsx
import { UserProvider } from '@auth0/nextjs-auth0/client';

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        <UserProvider>
          {children}
        </UserProvider>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```
- `UserProvider` makes the session available to client components via `useUser()`.

### 6. Protect routes with middleware
- Create `middleware.ts` at the project root:
```ts
import { withMiddlewareAuthRequired } from '@auth0/nextjs-auth0/edge';

export default withMiddlewareAuthRequired();

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/dashboard/:path*', '/settings/:path*', '/api/protected/:path*'],
};
```
- Unauthenticated users hitting protected routes are automatically redirected to Auth0 login.
- Adjust the `matcher` array to match your protected paths.

### 7. Access the session in Server Components
```tsx
import { getSession } from '@auth0/nextjs-auth0';

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const session = await getSession();
  if (!session) return <p>Not logged in</p>;
  return <p>Hello, {session.user.name}</p>;
}
```

### 8. Access the session in Client Components
```tsx
'use client';
import { useUser } from '@auth0/nextjs-auth0/client';

export function Profile() {
  const { user, isLoading } = useUser();
  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (!user) return <a href="/api/auth/login">Login</a>;
  return (
    <div>
      <img src={user.picture} alt={user.name} />
      <p>{user.name}</p>
      <a href="/api/auth/logout">Logout</a>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 9. Protect API routes
```ts
import { withApiAuthRequired, getSession } from '@auth0/nextjs-auth0';
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';

export const GET = withApiAuthRequired(async function handler(req) {
  const session = await getSession();
  return NextResponse.json({ user: session?.user });
});
```

### 10. Add roles and permissions (RBAC)
- In Auth0 dashboard: go to **User Management → Roles** and create roles (e.g., `admin`, `member`).
- Under **Actions → Flows → Login**, create an Action to attach roles to the token:
```js
exports.onExecutePostLogin = async (event, api) => {
  const namespace = 'https://your-app.com';
  if (event.authorization) {
    api.idToken.setCustomClaim(`${namespace}/roles`, event.authorization.roles);
    api.accessToken.setCustomClaim(`${namespace}/roles`, event.authorization.roles);
  }
};
```
- In your app, read roles from the session:
```ts
const session = await getSession();
const roles = session?.user['https://your-app.com/roles'] as string[] ?? [];
const isAdmin = roles.includes('admin');
```
- IMPORTANT: Claims must use a namespaced URL to avoid conflicts with reserved Auth0 claims.

### 11. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev` and visit `http://localhost:3000/api/auth/login` — you should see the Auth0 Universal Login page.
- After logging in, visit `/api/auth/me` — you should see your user profile JSON.
- Check the Network tab for a `appSession` cookie being set after login.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`AUTH0_SECRET must be 32 bytes or more`** — Generate with `openssl rand -hex 32` and paste the full value into `.env.local`.
- **`Callback URL mismatch`** — The URL in Auth0 dashboard Allowed Callback URLs must exactly match `AUTH0_BASE_URL + /api/auth/callback`. Check for trailing slashes.
- **`discovery_document_url`** — `AUTH0_ISSUER_BASE_URL` is missing `https://` or has a typo. It must be the full URL including the scheme.
- **`Session not found in Server Component`** — You called `getSession()` in a Server Component but forgot to await it, or you're using the old Pages Router method in App Router.
- **`useUser() must be wrapped in UserProvider`** — Add `<UserProvider>` to your root `app/layout.tsx`.
- **`withMiddlewareAuthRequired is not a function`** — Import from `@auth0/nextjs-auth0/edge`, not from `@auth0/nextjs-auth0`.
- **`Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'user')`** — `getSession()` returned `null`. User is not logged in. Add a null check.
- **Custom claims not appearing in session** — You added the Login Action but forgot to deploy it in Auth0 dashboard, or you're reading the wrong namespace string.
- **Social login not working** — In Auth0 dashboard, go to **Authentication → Social** and enable the social connection (e.g., Google). You also need to add the connection to your Application.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT use `auth0-js` or `@auth0/auth0-spa-js` in a Next.js project — these are SPA libraries that expose tokens client-side.
- Do NOT store `AUTH0_CLIENT_SECRET` in client-side code or expose it via a public API route.
- Do NOT skip `AUTH0_SECRET` — without it, the session cookie cannot be encrypted and the SDK throws immediately.
- Do NOT use the same `AUTH0_BASE_URL` for production and development — each environment needs its own Auth0 application or at least its own allowed callback URLs.
- Do NOT manually decode the JWT — use `getSession()` which handles verification for you.
- Do NOT forget to add production callback/logout URLs in the Auth0 dashboard before deploying — otherwise production login will fail with a callback URL mismatch.
- Do NOT use `withPageAuthRequired` (Pages Router) in the App Router — use middleware with `withMiddlewareAuthRequired` instead.
